<topic id="14790228-f45b-42d5-9b3e-f6b4ab932b9e" revisionNumber="0">
  <developerGlossaryDocument xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns="http://ddue.schemas.microsoft.com/authoring/2003/5">
    <glossary>
      <title>Glossary</title>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">AIP</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            An acronym that stands for Auto-Input Protection.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">Answer</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            A user's or bot's response to a challenge.  In AIP, the correct answer is a string of text that matches the text on the CAPTCHA image.  An incorrect answer does not match.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">CAPTCHA</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            An acronym that stands for Completely Automated Public Turing test to tell Computers and Humans Apart, trademarked by Carnegie Mellon University according to the
            following article: <externalLink><linkText>CAPTCHA. (2008, March 26).</linkText><linkUri>http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=CAPTCHA&amp;oldid=201120981</linkUri></externalLink> In Wikipedia, The Free Encyclopedia. Retrieved 09:01, March 27, 2008.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">Challenge,</term>
          <term termClass="">Test</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            A CAPTCHA image, being displayed on a web page, to which a user must respond with an answer by entering the text that they see on the image.  The result is pass or fail.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">Composite image</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            A graphic that is generated by an <codeEntityReference>T:DaveSexton.Web.Controls.AutoInputProtectionImage</codeEntityReference> implementation, consisting of a 
            background image and the CAPTCHA text, which is rendered by an <codeEntityReference>T:DaveSexton.Web.Controls.AutoInputProtectionTextProvider</codeEntityReference> 
            implementation.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">Line noise</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            A series of random, usually connected, lines that trick OCR software by adding ambiguity to a CAPTCHA image.  Line noise is not meant to be easily distinguishable 
            from the outline of actual characters that make up the text on the image.  The goal for line noise is to add enough ambiguity to trick OCR programs without reducing the 
            readability of the challenge to the point where people cannot pass the test themselves.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">OCR</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            An acronym that stands for Optical Character Recognition, which is a term used to describe the ability for software to parse text from images.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">Opacity</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            Refers to the ability to see through a color.  An opaque color is completely solid, while a semi-opaque color is partially see-through; i.e., translucent.
          </para>
          <para>
            In AIP opacity is typically specified as a floating point number between zero (fully transparent) and one (fully opaque).
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">Overlay</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            Refers to an <codeEntityReference>T:DaveSexton.Web.Controls.AutoInputProtectionFilterProvider</codeEntityReference> implementation that performs post-processing.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">Post-process</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            Refers to the ability of an <codeEntityReference>T:DaveSexton.Web.Controls.AutoInputProtectionFilterProvider</codeEntityReference> implementation to apply
            itself after the CAPTCHA text has been rendered on a surface image; i.e., a filter that applies to the composite image.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">Preprocess</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            Refers to the ability of an <codeEntityReference>T:DaveSexton.Web.Controls.AutoInputProtectionFilterProvider</codeEntityReference> implementation to apply
            itself before the CAPTCHA text has been rendered on a surface image.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">Provider</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            A type that derives from <codeEntityReference>T:System.Configuration.Provider.ProviderBase</codeEntityReference>.
          </para>
          <para>
            In the context of AIP a provider is a type that derives from <codeEntityReference>T:DaveSexton.Web.Controls.AutoInputProtectionTextProvider</codeEntityReference>,
            <codeEntityReference>T:DaveSexton.Web.Controls.AutoInputProtectionImageProvider</codeEntityReference> or 
            <codeEntityReference>T:DaveSexton.Web.Controls.AutoInputProtectionFilterProvider</codeEntityReference>, which are all subclasses of ProviderBase.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">Surface image</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            A graphic that is generated by an <codeEntityReference>T:DaveSexton.Web.Controls.AutoInputProtectionImage</codeEntityReference> implementation before
            an <codeEntityReference>T:DaveSexton.Web.Controls.AutoInputProtectionTextProvider</codeEntityReference> implementation renders the text, forming the composite image.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">Translucent</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            Partially see-through; i.e., not fully transparent and not fully opaque.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
      <glossaryEntry>
        <terms>
          <term termClass="">Validate</term>
        </terms>
        <definition>
          <para>
            The act of verifying user input against a CAPTCHA challenge.  The result is pass or fail.
          </para>
          <para>
            Input validation is typically accomplished in ASP.NET using <externalLink><linkText>validation controls</linkText><linkUri>http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/debza5t0.aspx</linkUri></externalLink>.
            <codeEntityReference>T:DaveSexton.Web.Controls.AutoInputProtectionControl</codeEntityReference> uses validators to enforce that input is required and to validate
            the input that is submitted.
          </para>
          <para>
            AutoInputProtectionControl will perform automatic validation during post backs when it's added to a web page.  The 
            <codeEntityReference>P:DaveSexton.Web.Controls.AutoInputProtectionControl.IsValid</codeEntityReference> property or the Page control's 
            <codeEntityReference>P:System.Web.UI.Page.IsValid</codeEntityReference> property can be used to check the result.
          </para>
        </definition>
      </glossaryEntry>
    </glossary>
  </developerGlossaryDocument>
